# subrecon

```
             __
   ___ __ __/ /  _______ _______  ___
  (_-</ // / _ \/ __/ -_) __/ _ \/ _ \
 /___/\_,_/_.__/_/  \__/\__/\___/_//_/
```

Subdomain recon chain: **enumerate → resolve → probe → filter**.

One command. Takes a domain, finds subdomains from multiple sources, resolves them, probes for live web servers, and filters by status code.

## Install

```bash
git clone https://github.com/t3lesph0re/subrecon.git
cd subrecon
pip install .
```

That's it. Now `subrecon` works from anywhere.

### Required CLI tools

These must be installed and in your `$PATH`:

| Tool | Purpose | Install (macOS) | Install (Linux) |
|------|---------|-----------------|-----------------|
| [assetfinder](https://github.com/tomnomnom/assetfinder) | subdomain enum | `brew install assetfinder` | `go install github.com/tomnomnom/assetfinder@latest` |
| [dnsx](https://github.com/projectdiscovery/dnsx) | DNS resolution | `brew install projectdiscovery/tap/dnsx` | `go install github.com/projectdiscovery/dnsx/cmd/dnsx@latest` |
| [httpx](https://github.com/projectdiscovery/httpx) | web probing | `brew install projectdiscovery/tap/httpx` | `go install github.com/projectdiscovery/httpx/cmd/httpx@latest` |
| [subfinder](https://github.com/projectdiscovery/subfinder) | extra enum sources (optional) | `brew install projectdiscovery/tap/subfinder` | `go install github.com/projectdiscovery/subfinder/v2/cmd/subfinder@latest` |

## Usage

```bash
# That's it
subrecon example.com

# With options
subrecon example.com -v                    # verbose — see tool output
subrecon example.com -o ~/recon/target     # custom output dir
subrecon example.com -s 200,301,302        # keep multiple status codes
subrecon example.com --no-filter           # skip filter step

# Cleanup
subrecon clean outputs/example.com
```

## How it works

```
subrecon example.com
```

| Step | Tool | Output |
|------|------|--------|
| 1. Enumerate | assetfinder + subfinder | `subs.txt` |
| 2. Resolve | dnsx | `resolved.txt` |
| 3. Probe | httpx | `live.txt` |
| 4. Filter | built-in | `live-200.txt` |

Results go to `outputs/<domain>/` by default.

